{{italic title}} [[File:EdinburghEncyclopediaAmerican.JPG|thumb|American reprint 1832]] The '''''Edinburgh Encyclopædia''''' was an encyclopaedia in 18 volumes, printed and published by [[William Blackwood]] and edited by [[David Brewster]] between 1808 and 1830. In competition with the Edinburgh-published ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]'',<ref name="Brewster">{{cite book|last=Brewster|first=David|title=The Edinburgh encyclopædia conducted by David Brewster, with the assistance of gentlemen eminent in science and literature, Volume 18|editor=[[David Brewster]]|publisher=[[J. and E. Parker]]|year=1832|isbn=978-0-415-18026-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0U5QAAAAMAAJ&dq=isbn%3A0415180260}}</ref> the ''Edinburgh Encyclopædia'' is generally considered to be strongest on scientific topics, where many of the articles were written by the editor.<ref name="Britannica">{{cite book|title=Encyclopædia Britannica|year=1902|edition=10|url=http://www.1902encyclopedia.com/B/BRE/david-brewster.html}}</ref>
The ''Edinburgh Encyclopædia'' was originally planned to encompassed 12 volumes, but by the time the final volume was published, in 1830, it counted 18 volumes. Some subjects, such as the [[polarization of light]] and [[electromagnetism]] hadn't even been heard of when the project began, and yet the Encyclopedia had articles on them. The electromagnetism article was even contributed by [[Hans Christian Ørsted]], the founder of modern electromagnetic studies. It also included information on contemporary events such as [[Christopher Hansteen]]'s 1829 expedition to Siberia.<ref>Robert Collison ''Encyclopedias: their history throughout the ages'' 2nd ed. New York and London; Haffner Publishing Company 1966 pp.175-6</ref>
In 1815 [[William Elford Leach]] published the first bibliography of entomology in Brewster's ''Edinburgh Encyclopædia'' (see [[Timeline of entomology – 1800–1850]]).
[[Joseph Parker (printer)|Joseph Parker]] of [[Philadelphia]] and [[Whiting & Watson]] of [[New York City]] printed [[United States|American]] editions, both in 1832.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}
==Contributors== A list of major contributors, with indications of their articles, was published in 1830.<ref name="Brewster1830">{{cite book|author=[[Sir David Brewster]]|title=The Edinburgh Encyclopædia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KT0gAQAAMAAJ&pg=PR9|accessdate=28 April 2012|year=1830|publisher=Printed for W. Blackwood|pages=ix–xiv}}</ref>
Other contributors – "Gentlemen Eminent in Science and Literature" – included [[Adam Anderson (physicist)|Adam Anderson]], [[Charles Babbage]], [[Thomas Carlyle]],<ref name="Literary gazette">{{cite book|title=The Literary gazette: A weekly journal of literature, science, and the fine arts|publisher=H. Colburn|year=1833|volume=17}}</ref> [[Robert Gordon (minister)|Robert Gordon]], [[Robert Edmond Grant]],<ref name="Desmond">{{cite book|last=Desmond|first=Adrian|authorlink=Adrian Desmond|author2=Parker, Sarah E.|title=The bibliography of Robert Edmond Grant (1793–1874)|date=October 2006|series=Archives of Natural History|volume=33}}</ref> [[John Leslie (physicist)|John Leslie]],<ref name="O'Connor">{{cite web|url=http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Biographies/Leslie.html|title=John Leslie|last=O'Connor|first=J J|author2=Robertson, E F|publisher=School of Mathematics and Statistics, University of St Andrews|accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref> [[Henry Liston]], [[John Gibson Lockhart]]<ref name="Literary gazette" /> and [[Thomas Telford]].
